Imagine you own a large house. If you measure all the empty floor space in every room, you have a total of 500 square meters of free space.
However, this free space isn't in one massive, empty ballroom. Instead, it is scattered all over the house in tiny 3 to 5 square meter chunks—a little 
space next to the sofa, a small gap in the hallway, and a corner of the kitchen. One day, you go shopping and buy a massive, custom-built, single-piece 
King Size Bed that requires a solid 20 square meters of space. You bring the bed to the front door and try to move it in.

- The Problem: You have 500 square meters of total free space, but you do not have a single, continuous 20-square-meter block of space anywhere in the house.
- The Result: The bed cannot enter the house.

In the programming world, the system throwing its hands in the air and saying "I can't fit this in here!" is exactly what an OutOfMemoryException is. 
The memory is "fragmented," so it cannot accommodate the large object.

## The Technical Reality

When your program runs, it requests memory from the operating system to store variables, objects, and data structures. This space is called the Heap.
As your program runs, it constantly creates and destroys objects. Over time, this leaves "holes" in the memory—just like the scattered empty spaces 
in the house. This is called Memory Fragmentation.

When you try to create a massive object—like a huge Array, a giant String, or loading a massive image file—the runtime requires contiguous memory. 
It needs one unbroken, continuous block of bytes to store that single object. If the system has 2GB of total free RAM, but the largest continuous 
block is only 10MB, trying to allocate a 20MB array will instantly trigger an OutOfMemoryException.

